Anonymous Thu 12 May 2022 19:10:57 No.47667652 Report
Quoted By: >>47667727 >>47668239
>>47666585
Both are big time sinks. Drawing produces quicker results. It's much easier to share art as well, the person looking at it doesn't need to invest possibly hours to consume it unlike writing. Both writing and drawing take a lot of practice and skill building. Both can fulfilling in different ways. You can tell stories with both through comics, for example.

For writing, don't expect it to be easier than art. The longer a story is the harder things become. There are easy stretches, but nearly everyone experiences boredom and frustration after writing the same thing for a long time. You have to ignore the urge to start new projects or confine them to idea notes, vignettes, and shitposts if you want to keep focused.
It's a lot harder to find knowledgeable, reliable help with writing than art. It takes time to read a story, time to process thoughts, and time to lay out advice and critique.

With either, do not make 4chan your primary audience or dumping grounds. It's a good place to start for honest opinions. But there's a wide range of insight you can get by posting across multiple websites. Then again, I get far more feedback and engagement outside of 4chan than I do here. Everyone's mileage will vary.
Leaves of Fall? Mostly a 4chan audience due to greentext if anything, but it's a very appreciative audience
HATSSSSS? Ao3 and 4chan, but Kaktus' shorter stories have gotten a lot of attention on SoFurry
Strong looks to have an even mix across the places he posts but he's in thread and could tell you better than me
The only place that doesn't work for shilling writing is twitter. People almost never click links there.

Anonymous Thu 12 May 2022 19:33:09 No.47668042 Report
Quoted By: >>47668239 >>47668264 >>47669732
>>47666585
Having people enjoy my writing is what motivated me to start to learn to draw in the first place. Just the idea that I could create something that people enjoyed was a new concept to me. It's hard to do both at once, and I find myself either focusing on writing or drawing from week to week. Drawing is much harder for me though, and I try to get in at least 30 mins of practice at that every day, even if writing is my focus at the time. The problem with drawing is that it's much easier to spend 2-4 hours grinding away at something, and then have to walk away feeling like you're no closer to achieving what you set out to draw when you sat down. At least my writers block manifests as me just staring at my notepad for 10 minutes completely uninspired and then getting distracted by something for half an hour, coming back, and spending another 10 minutes looking at my story without adding a single word. With drawing, I spend all that time actively trying to do it, and just ctrl+z ing over and over and over. It can be maddening. Drawing also has a much higher bar for "acceptable" I find. Okay writing can still be enjoyed as porn by someone who's looking for something that your story provides, even if it's not the best, cause there's more room for their own brain to fill in the gaps. Okay art isn't bad or anything by any means, but it's much more difficult to hit that "neuron activation" level than it is with writing. It will definitely make you slower at both, there's only so many hours in the day, but I find it to be worth it for me anyway. I'm starting to get to the point where I might become an active drawfag though. Pic related is a Pepper I drew today.

(1/2)

Anonymous Thu 12 May 2022 21:22:18 No.47670481 Report
Quoted By: >>47671539
>>47666585
Writing feels technically easier but that's probably mostly because it's the one I know how to do. I will say that I think coherent writing as a lower skill floor than coherent drawing. It's about as difficult to produce good work in either case, but the main drawbacks in writing are the generally much larger scope and difficulty of operating without feedback. Writing requires you to commit to single projects for much longer on average, and it is very difficult to self-evaluate for even fairly basic criteria. Scope is a double-edged sword, though. If you have a passion for telling stories specifically, the workload to tell a compelling story of a given length in writing is orders of magnitude less than to do it in images. I think there are also a few more avenues into writing enjoyable work. If you can sit down and tell a story around a campfire that your friends like, you will be able to write stories people enjoy fairly quickly and easily, even if your grammar and diction suck balls. Telling clean little stories like that was always my weakest facet, and it is a tragic weakness

A couple hours late but boy I guess I want an excuse to type.

what the other anons have been saying rings far truer to writing than any half-assed opinion I could give you. how I see it, with writing AND with art; both are timesinks to the bitter end. I believe writing feels easier like that one anon says because you can get better at writing passively, though telling stories or by consuming media. art is something you need to dedicate a space to. art really isn't something you can improve passively, and lord knows you won't feel the same short-term improvements you do through writing.

I may not seem like it, but I've started doing digital art since like, march of 2020. I've had explosive progress with my art cause I've just put my skull to the grindstone and haven't let up until recently. it's all about time.

but you want some pros and cons. kk dood ill try my best.

writing. fuck me, you can do ANYTHING with writing. describing sensations, amazing technologies, the pulse-pounding second by second DREAD your character can feel is second to none. art can SHOW a world, but writing can truly MAKE it.

art. they really do mean it when they say a picture can speak a thousand words. you have a concept for a character? you can SHOW what they look like. their stance, their build, EVERYTHING. explosive scenes in writing can be exciting, yeah. but with art, you can SHOW the explosion. SHOW the emotion. not everyone has time to read a book, but someone has time to glance by a piece. writing can MAKE you a character, but art? art can SHOW you a character. or something like that. I'm not a writer, lmao.

I've tried both. I def like art more. pretty pictures and all that. but fuck me, pictures cannot truly write a story.

so i guess, what do you want? how do you want to EVOLVE your ideas? ideas are just that, ideas. bits and pieces in the aether until given flesh. how do you want to turn your ideas into something more tangible? through art, or through writing?
